Free Trade Believers
From Cambridge — — Recently, I was invited to guest lecture in a globalization course taught by two Harvard colleagues. “I have to warn you.”
One of them had warned me beforehand: “These students are strong supporters of globalization.”
He had even asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and more than 90% chose the former.
And this was before he even started teaching the magic effect of comparative advantage.
We know that in a real survey, asking the same question to a representative sample - not Harvard students - would yield a completely different result.
In the United States, the ratio of those opposing trade restrictions to those supporting them is 2:1.
But the Harvard students' answers would not be particularly surprising.
Because people with higher technology and better education tend to be more in favor of free trade than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students have already anticipated their future (financial) prospects and made their decision accordingly.
Or perhaps, they don't actually understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately phrased the same question in a different way and emphasized the distribution effects that trade can have.
The consensus in favor of fair trade completely disappeared, and even faster than I had expected.
At the start, I asked if everyone agreed to participate in a particularly magical experiment.
I chose Nicholas and John as volunteers, and then told them that I could make $200 disappear from Nicholas's account — — Poof! — — while making John's account increase by $300, and through social engineering, the entire class could gain an additional $100 in value.
So will they let me play this little trick?
Only a small part agreed decisively, many hesitated, and even more people opposed the change.

It is clear that the students found it difficult to tolerate this significant income redistribution, even when the entire economic pie was being enlarged.
I then asked why most of them instinctively supported free trade, when free trade would actually lead to a similar – indeed, even greater – wealth redistribution from losers to winners.
The students looked stunned.
I continued, let's assume Nicholas and John both own a small competing company.
John worked harder, saved more, invested more, and produced better products, so he not only had $300 more than Nicholas but also drove Nicholas' company out of the market, resulting in a loss of $200.
So how many students voted in favor of this change?
This time, most voted in favor - in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then posed another assumption directly related to international trade.
If John were to drive Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or by outsourcing business processes to China where labor rights are not yet well-established?
Or by hiring child labor in Indonesia?
The level of approval for this transformation would decrease with each of the above options.
Moreover, technological innovation, just like trade, will put certain groups of people in a more vulnerable position. What is your attitude towards this?
Only a few students were willing to restrict the development of technology.
For almost everyone, the idea of banning the production of light bulbs in order to protect the jobs of candlemakers is a foolish one.
So, what the students are opposed to is not necessarily redistribution, but rather a specific form of redistribution.
Like most people, they are concerned about the fairness of the process.
If we want to judge the results of redistribution, we must know the objective environment that produced these results.
We won't be envious of Bill Gates' or Warren Buffett's enormous wealth, even if some of their competitors have been struggling, because they and their competitors all operate according to the same basic rules and face very similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett became rich through cheating, violating labor laws, destroying the environment, or using foreign government subsidies, our thoughts would be completely different.
If we can't tolerate redistribution achieved through violating widely accepted moral principles at home, why should we be okay with it just because it involves cross-border transactions?
Similarly, when we expect the redistributive effect to be achieved in the long run and everyone will ultimately benefit from it, we are likely to not care about the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that even though technology may bring short-term negative consequences to some people, we still want to promote its development.
On the other hand, when trade constantly affects the same group of people - low-educated blue-collar workers - we will be worried about globalization.
However, many economists ignore these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute concerns about globalization to stupid and selfish trade protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most important issue is actually a moral one.
Since they are unable to recognize that international trade sometimes - of course, not often - leads to unacceptable redistribution consequences that we cannot accept domestically, these economists also fail to intervene in public discussions appropriately.
But since they can't stand morally, how can they defend globalization so strongly?
When globalization occasionally raises a tricky question related to the legitimation of the redistribution effect, we shouldn't respond impulsively with trade restrictions.
There are many pros and cons that need to be weighed carefully, including the fact that globalization may cause more severe wealth deprivation to people in other places than to those in the US.
However, democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion on this issue and make more conscious and thoughtful decisions.
And the practice of being overly fond of globalization just because it has made the pie bigger will inevitably erode the legitimacy of globalization in the long run.
